# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a-with-ring-above-cyrillic] A with ring above is used only in the alphabet of the Selkup language, where it represents the open-mid back rounded vowel /ɔ/ or the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] It is similar in shape to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The lowercase version is often written in one of two forms: the double-storey |a| and single-storey |ɑ|.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The latter form is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In English, the name of the letter is the *long A* sound, pronounced /ˈeɪ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Its name in most other languages matches the letter's pronunciation in open syllables.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The earliest known ancestor of A is *aleph*—the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet—where it represented a glottal stop [ʔ], as Phoenician only used consonantal letters.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter representing a glottal stop—so they adapted the sign to represent the vowel /a/, calling the letter by the similar name *alpha*.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In the earliest Greek inscriptions dating to the 8th century BC following the Greek Dark Ages, the letter rests upon its side.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] However, in the later Greek alphabet it generally resembles the modern capital form—though many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to the Italian Peninsula, and they left the form of alpha unchanged.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] When the Romans adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write Latin, the resulting form used in the Latin script would come to be used to write many other languages, including English.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] During Roman times, there were many variant forms of the letter A.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] First was the monumental or lapidary style, which was used when inscribing on stone or other more permanent media.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] There was also a cursive style used for everyday or utilitarian writing, which was done on more perishable surfaces.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Due to the perishable nature of these surfaces, there are not as many examples of this style as there are of the monumental, but there are still many surviving examples of different types of cursive, such as majuscule cursive, minuscule cursive, and semi-cursive minuscule.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Variants also existed that were intermediate between the monumental and cursive styles.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The known variants include the early semi-uncial (c.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] 4th–8th centuries), and the late semi-uncial (c.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] At the end of the Roman Empire (5th century CE), several variants of the cursive minuscule developed through Western Europe.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Among these were the semi-cursive minuscule of Italy, the Merovingian script in France, the Visigothic script in Spain, and the Insular or Anglo-Irish semi-uncial or Anglo-Saxon majuscule of Great Britain.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] By the ninth century, the Caroline script, which was very similar to the present-day form, was the principal form used in book-making, before the advent of the printing press.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] This form was derived through a combining of prior forms.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] 15th-century Italy saw the formation of the two main variants that are known today.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] These variants, the *Italic* and *Roman* forms, were derived from the Caroline Script version.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The Italic form ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *script a*, is often used in handwriting; it consists of a circle with a vertical stroke on its right.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In the hands of medieval Irish and English writers, this form gradually developed from a 5th-century form resembling the Greek letter tau ⟨τ⟩.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The Roman form ⟨a⟩ is found in most printed material, and consists of a small loop with an arc over it.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Both derive from the majuscule form ⟨A⟩.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In Greek handwriting, it was common to join the left leg and horizontal stroke into a single loop, as demonstrated by the uncial version shown.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Many fonts then made the right leg vertical.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In some of these, the serif that began the right leg stroke developed into an arc, resulting in the printed form, while in others it was dropped, resulting in the modern handwritten form.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Graphic designers refer to the *Italic* and *Roman* forms as *single-decker a* and *double decker a* respectively.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Italic type is commonly used to mark emphasis or more generally to distinguish one part of a text from the rest set in Roman type.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] There are some other cases aside from italic type where *script a* ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *Latin alpha*, is used in contrast with Latin ⟨a⟩, such as in the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In English, ⟨a⟩ is the indefinite article (with the alternative form *an* when followed by a vowel).
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The double ⟨aa⟩ sequence does not occur in native English words, but is found in some words derived from foreign languages such as *Aaron* and *aardvark*.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] However, ⟨a⟩ occurs in many common digraphs, all with their own sound or sounds, particularly ⟨ai⟩, ⟨au⟩, ⟨aw⟩, ⟨ay⟩, ⟨ea⟩ and ⟨oa⟩.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] In most languages that use the Latin alphabet, ⟨a⟩ denotes an open unrounded vowel, such as /a/, /ä/, or /ɑ/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] An exception is Saanich, in which ⟨a⟩—and the glyph ⟨Á⟩—stands for a close-mid front unrounded vowel /e/.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The Latin letters ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ have Unicode encodings U+0041 A LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0061 a LATIN SMALL LETTER A.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] These are the same code points as those used in ASCII and ISO 8859.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] There are also precomposed character encodings for ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ with diacritics, for most of those listed above; the remainder are produced using combining diacritics.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] Variant forms of the letter have unique code points for specialist use: the alphanumeric symbols set in mathematics and science, Latin alpha in linguistics, and halfwidth and fullwidth forms for legacy CJK font compatibility.
[src:a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic/a] The Cyrillic and Greek homoglyphs of the Latin ⟨A⟩ have separate encodings U+0410 А CYRILLIC CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0391 Α GREEK CAPITAL LETTER ALPHA.
